Flour Babies is a day school novel for young adults , written by Anne Fine and published by Hamilton 1992 .
In Another Light is the fifth novel by Scottish writer Andrew Greig .
The Sixth Day and Other Tales , written by Primo Levi , is a collection of short stories , originally published in Storie naturali and Vizio di forma .
John Dies at the End is a comic horror novel written by David Wong that was first published online as a webserial beginning in 2001 , then as an edited manuscript in 2004 , and a printed paperback in 2007 , published by Permuted Press .
Screwtop Thompson , Booker Prize - shortlisted author Magnus Mills ' third collection of short stories , brings together ten short tales that `` trundle gently between the ordinary , absurd and the outright surreal . ''
One Morning in Maine is a picture book by Robert McCloskey set in Brooksville , Maine .
The Mistress of the Inn ( Italian : La locandiera ) , also translated as The Innkeeper Woman or Mirandolina ( after the play 's main character ) , is a 1753 three - act comedy by the Italian playwright Carlo Goldoni about a coquette .
Ashen Victor , known in Japan as Haisha ( 灰者 ) , is a futuristic manga by Yukito Kishiro , taking place in the same universe as his Battle Angel Alita series , specifically in the Scrapyard .
Spindle 's End is a retelling of Sleeping Beauty by author Robin McKinley , published in 2000 .
Absolute Friends is an espionage novel by John le Carré published in December 2003 .
A Dictionary of Modern English Usage ( 1926 ) , by Henry Watson Fowler ( 1858 - -1933 ) , is a style guide to British English usage , pronunciation , and writing .
The Black Gryphon is the first novel in the chronological timeline of the Valdemar Saga by author Mercedes Lackey , although not published until 1994 .
Franny and Zooey is a book by American author J. D. Salinger which comprises his short story `` Franny '' and novella Zooey /ˈzoʊ.iː/.
The Khaki Mafia is a novel about the Vietnam War by Robin Moore and June Collins , published by Crown in 1971 .
Evangelii gaudium ( English : The Joy of the Gospel ) is a 2013 apostolic exhortation by Pope Francis on `` the church 's primary mission of evangelization in the modern world . ''
Maus is a graphic novel by American cartoonist Art Spiegelman , serialized from 1980 to 1991 .
Very Hard Choices is a science - fiction / suspense - mystery novel from Canadian science fiction author Spider Robinson , released in June 2008 .
On War Against the Turk ( German : Vom Kriege wider die Türken ) was a book written by Martin Luther in 1528 and published in 1529 .
Midnight Lamp , first published in 2003 , is the third of a series of five books written by Gwyneth Jones and set in a near - future version of the United Kingdom .
Industrial Democracy ( 1st edn 1897 ; 9th edn 1926 ) is a book written by British socialist reformers Sidney Webb and Beatrice Webb , concerning the organisation of trade unions and collective bargaining .
The Girl from Nongrim Hills is a 2013 fiction novel by Indian author Ankush Saikia .
Samurai Executioner , known in Japan as Kubikiri Asa ( 首斬り朝 ) , is a 10-volume manga created by writer Kazuo Koike and artist Goseki Kojima , the same team that created the popular Lone Wolf and Cub series .
A Planet Called Utopia is a science fiction novel written by J. T. McIntosh and first published in August , 1979 in New York by Zebra Books .
The Road to Gandolfo is a story by Michael Shepherd ( a pen name used by Robert Ludlum ) about General MacKenzie Hawkins ( `` The Hawk '' ) , a military legend and Army veteran .
`` The God Stealer '' is a short story by Filipino National Artist F. Sionil José .
Tales of Magic and Mystery is a 1985 anthology of 11 fairy tales from around the world that have been collected and retold by Ruth Manning - Sanders .
`` The Man Who Would Be King '' ( 1888 ) is a novella by Rudyard Kipling .
Blood & Water was a 2003 five - issue horror comic book limited series written by Judd Winick and illustrated by Tomm Coker , with covers by Brian Bolland .
Servant of Two Masters ( Italian : Il servitore di due padroni ) is a comedy by the Italian playwright Carlo Goldoni written in 1746 .
`` Quench the Spark '' ( also translated as `` A Spark Neglected Burns the House '' ) is a short story by Russian author Leo Tolstoy first published in 1885 .
The Book on Adler ( subtitle : The Religious Confusion of the Present Age , Illustrated by Magister Adler as a Phenomenon , A Mimical Monograph ) is a work by the Danish philosopher Søren Kierkegaard , written during his second authorship , and was published posthumously in 1872 .
The Torment of Others is a crime novel by Scottish author Val McDermid , and is the fourth entry in her popular Carol Jordan and Dr. Tony Hill series , which has been successfully adapted into the television series Wire in the Blood .
Neptune 's Brood is a science fiction novel by British author Charles Stross , set in the same universe as Saturn 's Children , but thousands of years later and with all new characters .
Unfinished Tales ( full title Unfinished Tales of Númenor and Middle - earth ) is a collection of stories and essays by J. R. R. Tolkien that were never completed during his lifetime , but were edited by his son Christopher Tolkien and published in 1980 .
Eisenvogel is a Swiss book published by the Swiss - Tibetan writer , filmdirector ( Who Killed Johnny ) and actress Yangzom Brauen .
`` The Tercentenary Incident '' is a science - fiction / mystery short story by Isaac Asimov .
Wolf Hunting is a novel in the Firekeeper Saga series by Jane Lindskold .
The Estoria de España , also known in the 1906 edition of Ramón Menéndez Pidal as the Primera Crónica General , is a history book written on the initiative of Alfonso X of Castile `` El Sabio '' ( `` the Wise '' ) , who was actively involved in the editing .
Social Statics , or The Conditions essential to Happiness specified , and the First of them Developed is an 1851 book by the British polymath Herbert Spencer .
Robert Helmont ( 1874 ; English : Robert Helmont , The Diary of a Recluse , 1870 - 1871 ( 1892 ) ) is a novella by French author Alphonse Daudet .
Bunduki is a 1975 novel by J. T. Edson , and the first work in the Bunduki series that followed .
The Pixilated Peeress is a fantasy novel written by L. Sprague de Camp and Catherine Crook de Camp .
The Mummies of Guanajuato is a 1978 book which reprints Ray Bradbury 's novelette , `` The Next in Line '' , illustrated with photographs , by Archie Lieberman , of the actual mummies discovered in Guanajuato which inspired the story .
`` Lt . Gov. You 've Got ta Love '' ( also called `` David Dewhurst : Lt . Gov. You 've Got ta Love '' ) was a political advertisement issued by incumbent David Dewhurst 's campaign on YouTube during the 2014 primary runoff for Lieutenant Governor of Texas against Dan Patrick .
The Ghost and the Goth is a 2010 paranormal romance young adult novel written by Stacey Kade and published by Hyperion Books .
The White Company is a historical adventure by Arthur Conan Doyle set during the Hundred Years ' War .
`` I Am the Doorway '' is a short story by Stephen King , first published in the March 1971 issue of Cavalier magazine , and later collected in King 's 1978 collection Night Shift .
Rebel Angels is the second book in a fantasy trilogy by Libba Bray .
Le parti pris des choses is a collection of 32 short to medium - length prose poems by French poet and essayist Francis Ponge first published in 1942 ( see 1942 in poetry ) .
Running from the Deity ( 2005 ) is a science fiction novel written by Alan Dean Foster .
Time and Mr. Bass is a 1967 children 's science fiction novel by Canadian author Eleanor Cameron .
The Fox on the Fairway is a comedy by Ken Ludwig that premiered at the Signature Theatre , Arlington , Virginia , in 2010 .
Shrink Yourself ( 2007 ) is a book on emotional eating by Roger Gould .
The Rape of the A*P*E * is a book by Allan Sherman , published in September 1973 by the Putnam Publishing Group , regarding sex and its historical repression and resurgence in the United States .
The Bottle Imp is an 1891 short story by the Scottish author Robert Louis Stevenson usually found in the short story collection Island Nights ' Entertainments .
The Adventures and Misadventures of Maqroll ( orig . Spanish es : Empresas y Tribulaciones de Maqroll el Gaviero ) is a compilation of novellas by Colombian author Álvaro Mutis .
A Clubbable Woman is a crime novel by Reginald Hill , the first novel in the Dalziel and Pascoe series .
Observations on Man , his Frame , his Duty , and his Expectations is 18th - century British philosopher David Hartley 's major work .
A Nursery Tale ( Russian : Сказка , Skazka ) is a short story by Vladimir Nabokov first published in the expatriate Russian newspaper Rul ' on 27 and 29 June 1926 and in the book form in The Return of Chorb in 1930 .
Min Fynske Barndom , translated into English as My Childhood , is Carl Nielsen 's autobiographical account of his childhood on the Danish island of Funen .
Black Star Rising , published in 1986 , is a science fiction novel by American author Frederik Pohl .
Satiromastix , or The Untrussing of the Humorous Poet is a late Elizabethan stage play by Thomas Dekker , one of the plays involved in the Poetomachia or War of the Theatres .
Theory and Practice of Muslim State in India is a book by historian K. S. Lal published by Aditya Prakashan in 1999 .
The Atrocity Exhibition is an experimental collection of `` condensed novels '' by British writer J. G. Ballard .
Owing to Bill Watterson 's principled refusal to license his comic strip for merchandise in general , Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes is an exceptional item ; a license was granted to the authors after they personally communicated to Watterson the success they had using his comic strip to teach children with learning disabilities .
Spanking Shakespeare ( 2007 ) is the debut novel by Jake Wizner .
July 's People is a 1981 novel by the South African writer Nadine Gordimer .
The Man Who Fell in Love with the Moon is a 1991 novel by American author Tom Spanbauer set at the beginning of the 20th century .
War of the Rats is a World War II fiction novel written by David L. Robbins in 1999 .
Pyrrhus and Cineas ( Original title : Pyrrhus et Cinéas ) is Simone de Beauvoir 's first philosophical essay .
When Colts Ran is a 2010 novel by Australian novelist Roger McDonald .
Step on a Crack is the first novel in the Michael Bennett series by James Patterson and Michael Ledwidge featuring Detective Michael Bennett and his 10 kids .
Tomorrow Stories was an American comic book series created by Alan Moore for his America 's Best Comics ( ABC ) line , published by Wildstorm ( now a subsidiary of DC Comics ) .
Mary Queen of Scots Got Her Head Chopped Off is a 1987 play by Liz Lochhead .
Elegiasta oodiin is a 1921 a collection of poems by Finnish poet Aaro Hellaakoski .
A ribbon of poems ( Dutch : Een lent van vaerzen ) was the literary debut of Dutch writer Louis Couperus .
The Oakdale Affair and The Rider is a collection of two short novels by Edgar Rice Burroughs .
On the Heavens ( Greek : Περὶ οὐρανοῦ , Latin : De Caelo or De Caelo et Mundo ) is Aristotle 's chief cosmological treatise : written in 350 BC it contains his astronomical theory and his ideas on the concrete workings of the terrestrial world .
Secrets at Sea is a 2011 children 's novel written by Newbery medalist Richard Peck and illustrated by award - winning artist Kelly Murphy .
The Way We Live Now is a satirical novel by Anthony Trollope , published in London in 1875 after first appearing in serialised form .
The Royal Writ of the Foundation of the City of Tlaxcala , Mexico ( in Spanish : Real cédula de la fundación de la ciudad de Tlaxcala , México ) is the historical document issued by decree of Charles V on April 22 , 1535 , in Madrid , Spain , bestowing Tlaxcala the title of city .
Dark Star Safari ( 2002 ) is a written account of a trip taken by author Paul Theroux ' overland from Cairo to Cape Town ' via trains , buses , cars , and armed convoy .
Mota Coqueiro , ou A Pena de Morte ( in English : Mota Coqueiro , or The Capital Punishment ) is a 1877 novel by Brazilian journalist and writer José do Patrocínio .
Spadework is a novel by Canadian writer Timothy Findley set in the theater world of Stratford , Ontario .
As part of Marvel NOW ! , a new volume of Uncanny X - Men was launched in February 2013 with an April 2013 cover date , written by Brian Michael Bendis , who is also writing another X - Men title , All - New X - Men , and drawn by Chris Bachalo .
The Tumbled House is a suspense novel written by Winston Graham , who is most famous for the Poldark series of historical novels .
Myra Breckinridge is a 1968 satirical novel by Gore Vidal written in the form of a diary .
The One O'Clock Chop is a young adult novel by written by Ralph Fletcher , first published in 2007 .
Sisterhood Everlasting is the fifth and last novel in Ann Brashares 's `` Sisterhood '' series .
Sailing Alone Around the World ( 1900 ) is a sailing memoir by Joshua Slocum about his single - handed global circumnavigation aboard the sloop Spray .
The Folk of the Fringe ( 1989 ) is a collection of post - apocalyptic stories by American writer Orson Scott Card .
A Turn in the South is a travelogue of the American South written by Nobel Prize - winning writer V. S. Naipaul .
The Very Hungry Caterpillar is a children 's picture book designed , illustrated and written by Eric Carle , first published by the World Publishing Company in 1969 , later published by Penguin Putnam .
Concept of the Corporation ( 1946 ) is a book by management professor and sociologist Peter Drucker .
`` Cock - A - Doodle - Doo ! or , The Crowing of the Nobel Cock Beneventano '' is an 1853 short story by the American writer Herman Melville .
Heimat ist das , was gesprochen wird ( `` Home Is What Is Spoken There '' ) is a book by Nobel Prize - winning author Herta Müller .
Celebrations , Rituals of Peace and Prayer is a collection of poetry by African - American writer and poet Maya Angelou , published by Random House in 2006 .
The Naked Face is the first novel ( 1970 ) written by Sidney Sheldon .
Rex Libris is a science fiction / humor comic book series written and illustrated by James Turner .
Kiss the Dead is a 2012 New York Times bestselling erotic thriller by novelist Laurell K. Hamilton .
Does n't Anyone Blush Anymore ? is a book on love and intimacy by Rabbi Manis Friedman , a Chabad Hasidic author and lecturer .
The Magehound is a fantasy novel by Elaine Cunningham , set in the world of the Forgotten Realms , and based on the Dungeons & Dragons role - playing game .
The 12.30 from Croydon ( U.S. title : Wilful and Premeditated ) is a detective novel by Freeman Wills Crofts first published in 1934 .
The History of The Hobbit is a two - volume study of J. R. R. Tolkien 's The Hobbit .
Holy Deadlock is a 1934 satirical novel by the English author A. P. Herbert , which aimed to highlight the perceived inadequacies and absurdities of contemporary divorce law .
Woyzeck ( German pronunciation : ( ˈvɔʏtsɛk ) ) is a stage play written by Georg Büchner .
Merchants of Doubt is a 2010 non - fiction book by American historians of science Naomi Oreskes and Erik M. Conway .
Johannes Cabal the Necromancer is a 2009 supernatural fiction and black comedy novel written by Jonathan L. Howard .
The Runaway Summer of Davie Shaw is a book by Mario Puzo , first published in 1966 .
Chinese Destinies ( 1933 ) is a collection of essays about China and Chinese lives by Agnes Smedley , a left - wing journalist .
`` How Watson Learned the Trick '' is a Sherlock Holmes parody written by Arthur Conan Doyle in 1922 .
Up from Jericho Tel is a children 's novel written and illustrated by E. L. Konigsburg , published by Atheneum Books in 1986 .
Wings of Hell is a science fiction novel by David Sherman and Dan Cragg ; it was released on December 30 , 2008 .
The Fantasy / Science Fiction novel No Present Like Time ( 2005 ) by Steph Swainston is the sequel to the critically acclaimed The Year of Our War ( 2004 ) .
Mannorð ( ' Reputation ' or , in the author 's translation , ' Repute ' or ' Ill repute ' ) is a novel by Bjarni Bjarnason , published by Uppheimar in 2011 .
The Darkangel Trilogy is a series of high fantasy novels by American author Meredith Ann Pierce published between 1982 and 1990 .
Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl is an autobiography by a young mother and fugitive slave published in 1861 by L. Maria Child , who edited the book for its author , Harriet Ann Jacobs .
Babouk is a political - themed novel by Guy Endore , a fictionalized account of the Haitian Revolution told through the eyes of its titular slave .
La cuisine pour tous , Je sais cuisiner , The French Pocket Cookbook , or I Know How to Cook is a French cookbook edited by Ginette Mathiot and H. Delage .
Marie Tudor is an 1833 play by the French writer Victor Hugo .
Tales from the Political Trenches is a 2012 Australian political memoir by journalist and former Australian Labor Party politician Maxine McKew .
Angel of Ruin ( also known as Fallen Angel ) is a 2001 horror novel by Kim Wilkins .
The Perl Cookbook is written by Tom Christiansen and Nathan Torkington , and published by O'Reilly .
Lady Midnight is a young adult contemporary novel by Cassandra Clare .
The Gashlycrumb Tinies : or , After the Outing is an abecedarian book written by Edward Gorey that was first published in 1963 .
A Personal Matter ( Japanese : 個人的な体験 ; Kojinteki na taiken ) is a novel by Japanese writer Kenzaburō Ōe .
Contingency , Irony , and Solidarity ( 1989 ) , is a book by American philosopher Richard Rorty , based on two sets of lectures he gave at University College , London , and at Trinity College , Cambridge .
Poèmes saturniens is the first collection of poetry by Paul Verlaine , first published in 1866 .
Keeper of Dreams ( 2008 ) is a short story collection by Orson Scott Card .
Afternoon Men is the first published novel by the English writer Anthony Powell .
Red Inferno : 1945 is a 2010 novel written by Robert Conroy , the author of other alternate history novels .
The Lettres provinciales ( Provincial letters ) are a series of eighteen letters written by French philosopher and theologian Blaise Pascal under the pseudonym Louis de Montalte .
Mother of Kings is a historical novel by Poul Anderson .
The Fig Leaves Are Falling is a musical with a book and lyrics by Allan Sherman and music by Albert Hague .
The School for Husbands is a play written by Molière and originally performed in 1661 in Paris .
Calendar of Regrets is a postmodern novel by Lance Olsen , published by Fiction Collective Two in 2010 .
The Secret of the Nagas is the second novel of the Shiva trilogy series by the Indian author Amish Tripathi .
The World that was Ours ( 1967 ) is Hilda Bernstein 's personal account of life in Johannesburg under the oppressive surveillance of the apartheid regime .
If I Had One Wish is a young adult novel by Jackie French Koller , about a teenager named Alex Lansing , whose little brother Stevie is always getting him in trouble .
The American Crisis is a pamphlet series by 18th century Enlightenment philosopher and author Thomas Paine , originally published from 1776 to 1783 during the American Revolution .
The Young Lions ( 1948 ) is a novel by Irwin Shaw about three soldiers in World War II .
Always Outnumbered , Always Outgunned is a 1997 crime novel by Walter Mosley .
De Natura Fossilium is a scientific text written by Georg Bauer also known as Georgius Agricola , first published in 1546 .
The Lure of the Mask is a 1908 novel by Harold MacGrath that was the fourth - best selling book in the United States for that year .
The IHOP Papers is the debut novel of American author Ali Liebegott , and was first published on December 13 , 2006 by Carroll & Graf .
The Roadmender is a 1902 Christian spiritual book by Margaret Barber , writing under the pseudonym Michael Fairless .
Written in Bone is a novel written by the British crime fiction writer Simon Beckett , first published in 2007 .
Devil 's Cub is a Georgian romance novel written by Georgette Heyer .
Clotel ; or , The President 's Daughter is an 1853 novel by United States author and playwright William Wells Brown about Clotel and her sister , fictional slave daughters of Thomas Jefferson .
New Finnish Grammar ( Italian : Nuova grammatica finlandese ) is a 2000 novel by the Italian writer Diego Marani .
The British Edda is a 1930 English , Sumerian and Egyptian linguistics and mythology book written by Laurence Waddell about the adventures of El , Wodan and Loki forming an Eden Triad in the Garden of Eden .
`` The Young Folks '' was J. D. Salinger 's first published story , published in Whit Burnett 's Story magazine in the March--
The Removers is a spy novel by Donald Hamilton first published in 1961 .
Sister Carrie ( 1900 ) is a novel by Theodore Dreiser about a young country girl who moves to the big city where she starts realizing her own American Dream , first as a mistress to men that she perceives as superior , and later becoming a famous actress .
Romancero Gitano ( translated as Gypsy Ballads ) is a poetry collection by Spanish writer Federico García Lorca , published in 1928 .
The Oakdale Affair is a short contemporary mystery novel by Edgar Rice Burroughs .
Dungeonscape was released in February 2007 , and was written by Jason Bulmahn and Rich Burlew .
Empty World ( 1977 ) is a apocalyptic fiction novel written by John Christopher aimed at an adolescent audience .
Último round ( the title translates as Last Round , as in boxing ) is a two - volume work by Julio Cortázar published by Siglo XXI Editores in 1969 .
With Shuddering Fall is the first novel by American author Joyce Carol Oates .
Diana of the Crossways is a novel by George Meredith which was published in 1885 .
`` In Flanders Fields '' is a war poem in the form of a rondeau , written during the First World War by Canadian physician Lieutenant - Colonel John McCrae .
Quest for Lost Heroes , published in 1990 , is a novel by British fantasy writer David Gemmell .
Théodore Poussin is a comic book series created by French writer Frank Le Gall about a glasses - wearing hero - it was first published in 1984 , in Spirou magazine .
Do n't You Dare Read This , Mrs. Dunphrey is a 1996 young adult novel written by Margaret Peterson Haddix .
Jason and Marceline is a 1986 young adult novel by Jerry Spinelli .
Flatterland is a 2001 book by mathematician and science popularizer Ian Stewart about non - Euclidean geometry .
The Five Greatest Warriors is the third thriller novel in the Jack West Jr. series , by the Australian writer Matthew Reilly .
The Complete Opera Book is a guide to operas by American music critic and author Gustav Kobbé first published ( posthumously ) in the United States in 1919 and the United Kingdom in 1922 .
Rights of Man ( 1791 ) , a book by Thomas Paine , including 31 articles , posits that popular political revolution is permissible when a government does not safeguard the natural rights of its people .
The Iron Druid Chronicles is a series of urban fantasy novels , written by Kevin Hearne and published by Del Rey Books .
The Legend of Sun Knight ( simplified Chinese : 吾命骑士 ; traditional Chinese : 吾命騎士 ; Pinyin : wú mìng qíshì ) is a Taiwanese light novel series written by Yu Wo .
The Boy Detective Fails is the fourth novel by Chicago author Joe Meno , released by Punk Planet Books in 2006 .
Meaning and Purpose , written by Kenneth Walker ( author ) , was first published in September 1944 by Jonathan Cape , London , and republished by Pelican books in 1950 .
Lives of the Monster Dogs ( 1997 ) is a novel by Kirsten Bakis first published by Farrar , Straus & Giroux .
Bring the Jubilee by Ward Moore is a 1953 novel of alternate history .
The Infernal is a 1997 horror / fantasy novel by Kim Wilkins .
`` A Season in Hell '' ( French : Une Saison en Enfer ) is an extended poem in prose written and published in 1873 by French writer Arthur Rimbaud .
Abeng ( Ä běng ) is a novel related to Maroons published in 1984 by Michelle Cliff .
The Genocidal Healer is a 1992 science fiction novel by author James White and is part of his Sector General series .
Sons of Cain is a 1985 play by David Williamson about three female investigative reporters .
`` Dragon and Phoenix '' is the second of the Dragonlord series by Joanne Bertin and was published in 1999 .
The View from the Seventh Layer is a collection of thirteen short stories by American author Kevin Brockmeier .
Robot Dreams ( 1986 ) is a collection of science fiction short stories by Isaac Asimov , illustrated by Ralph McQuarrie .
Dragon and Soldier is a 2004 science fiction novel by Timothy Zahn and the second book in his Dragonback series .
Ham on Rye is a 1982 semi - autobiographical novel by American author and poet Charles Bukowski .
The Forever War ( 1974 ) is a military science fiction novel by American author Joe Haldeman , telling the contemplative story of soldiers fighting an interstellar war between Man and the Taurans .
Poussy is a Belgian comic strip created in 1949 by Peyo .
The Reluctant Tommy is a book written by Ronald Skirth who was a member of the Royal Garrison Artillery during the First World War .
The Global 2000 Report to the President was commissioned by President Jimmy Carter on May 23 , 1977 .
The New Soldier was published as both a hard and soft cover book in October , 1971 , by Vietnam Veterans Against the War .
Movements in European History was a school textbook , originally published by Oxford University Press , by the English author D. H. Lawrence .
The Sporting Club is the 1968 debut novel of author Thomas McGuane .
Waiting for the Mahatma is a 1955 novel by R. K. Narayan .
A Suitable Boy is a novel by Vikram Seth , published in 1993 .
Excellent Cadavers is a 1995 non - fiction book by American author Alexander Stille about the Sicilian Mafia , concentrating on magistrate Giovanni Falcone 's fight against the Mafia and his 1992 assassination .
Children of the Atom is a 1953 science fiction novel by Wilmar H. Shiras , which has been listed as one of `` The Most Significant SF & Fantasy Books of the Last 50 Years , 1953 - 2002 . ''
The Hungry Man ( ISBN 974 - 345 - 211 - 7 ) is a book written and illustrated by Oren Ginzburg in 2004 .
The Battle of the Books is the name of a short satire written by Jonathan Swift and published as part of the prolegomena to his A Tale of a Tub in 1704 .
Ensign O'Toole and Me is the title of a 1957 semi - autobiographical novel by William Lederer .
Honour Among Thieves ( 1993 ) is a novel by English author Jeffrey Archer .
The Law of Success is a 1925 book -- actually in the form of a set of 15 separate booklets -- by Napoleon Hill .
The Secret of Platform 13 is a children 's novel by Eva Ibbotson , and illustrated by Sue Porter , first published in 1994 .
The Bitter Price of Love , published in 1995 , is one of the `` Single '' novels written by Amanda Browning and published by Harlequin Mills & Boon .
`` The Red - Headed League '' is one of the 56 Sherlock Holmes short stories written by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle .
Return of the Bunny Suicides ( 2004 ) is the second bestselling book of black comedy cartoons by Andy Riley that depict the various ways bunnies attempt to kill themselves .
The Second Mrs. Giaconda , later The Second Mrs. Gioconda , is a historical novel for children by E. L. Konigsburg .
World of Trouble is a 2014 American soft science fiction mystery novel by Ben H. Winters and published by Quirk Books .
`` The Brave Little Tailor '' or `` The Valiant Little Tailor '' or `` The Gallant Tailor '' is a German fairy tale collected by the Brothers Grimm , tale number 20 .
Salmonella Men on Planet Porno ( 2006 ) is a collection of short stories by Japanese science fiction and metafiction writer Yasutaka Tsutsui , in English translation by Andrew Driver .
Crampton Hodnet is a comic novel by Barbara Pym , published posthumously in 1985 .
Alfred and Emily is a book by Doris Lessing in a new hybrid form .
Japan 's Imperial Conspiracy is a nonfiction historical work by David Bergamini .
`` Sorry , Right Number '' is a teleplay written by author Stephen King for an episode of the horror anthology series Tales from the Darkside .
The Doings of Raffles Haw ( 1891 ) is a novel by Scottish author Sir Arthur Conan Doyle .
The Country of the Blind and Other Stories is a collection of thirty - three fantasy and science fiction short stories written by the English author H. G. Wells between 1894 and 1909 .
Sonnet 152 is a sonnet by William Shakespeare .
Feluda ( Bengali : ফেলুদা ) , or Prodosh Chandra Mitra , ( Bengali : প্রদোষ চন্দ্র মিত্র ) , who also uses the Anglicised name Pradosh C. Mitter , is a fictional private investigator starring in a series of Bengali novels and short stories written by Indian Bengali film director and writer Satyajit Ray .
Your Eyelids Are Growing Heavy is the fourth crime novel by the American writer Barbara Paul .
The Marrow of Tradition ( 1901 ) is a historical novel by the African - American author Charles Chesnutt , set at the time and portraying a fictional account of the Wilmington Insurrection of 1898 in Wilmington , North Carolina .
I Am Spock is the second volume of actor and director Leonard Nimoy 's autobiography .
The Rogue Mage series of fantasy novels were written by Faith Hunter about races of beings inhabiting a post - apocalyptic Earth of the not - too distant future .
The Day of the Locust is a 1939 novel by American author Nathanael West , set in Hollywood , California .
The War of the Worlds is a science fiction novel by English author H. G. Wells first serialized in 1897 in the UK by Pearson 's Magazine and in the US by Cosmopolitan magazine .
The First Philippic was delivered by the Athenian statesman and orator Demosthenes between 351 BC-350 BC . It constitutes the first speech of the prominent politician against Philip II of Macedon .
The Twilight of the Grey Gods , also known as The Grey God Passes , is a short story by Robert E. Howard that blends history and fantasy .
Lament for a Nation is a 1965 essay of political philosophy by Canadian philosopher George Grant .
The Legend of Thyl Ulenspiegel and Lamme Goedzak ( French : La Légende et les Aventures héroïques , joyeuses et glorieuses d'Ulenspiegel et de Lamme Goedzak au pays de Flandres et ailleurs ) is a 1867 novel by Belgian author Charles De Coster .
Henry and Ribsy is the third book in the Henry Huggins series of humorous children 's novels written by Beverly Cleary .
Darkness , Tell Us is a 1991 horror novel by Richard Laymon .
The Dying of the Light is a 1993 crime novel by Michael Dibdin set in a nursing home .
The Memory Keeper 's Daughter is a novel by American author Kim Edwards that tells the story of a man who gives away his newborn daughter , who has Down syndrome , to one of the nurses .
The Rosales Saga , also known as the Rosales Novels , is a series of five historical and political novels written by Filipino National Artist F. Sionil José .
Cavalier , passe ton chemin ! ( `` horseman , pass by ! '' ) is a 2005 book by the French writer Michel Déon .
Ascending is a science fiction novel by the Canadian writer James Alan Gardner , published in 2001 by HarperCollins Publishers under its various imprints .
The Slow Natives ( 1965 ) is a Miles Franklin Award winning novel by Australian author Thea Astley , the first of her record number of four wins .
Introduction to the Devout Life ( French : Introduction à la vie dévote ) is a book written by St. Francis de Sales , the first edition being published in 1609 .
Universi Dominici gregis is an Apostolic Constitution of the Catholic Church issued by Pope John Paul II on February 22 , 1996 .
The Gospel of Buddha was an 1894 book by Paul Carus .
Folk Stories from Southern Nigeria is a book by Elphinstone Dayrell , introduction by Andrew Lang , published in 1910 .
Point & Click Linux ! ( ISBN 978 - 0131488724 ) is a 2004 book / video combination from NewsForge and Slashdot editor Robin `` Roblimo '' Miller and published by Addison - Wesley .
This Is How You Lose Her is the second collection of short stories by Junot Díaz .
Futility , or the Wreck of the Titan is an 1898 novella written by Morgan Robertson .
The Happy Lion ( ISBN 0 - 375 - 82759 - 5 ) is a 1954 children 's picture book by Louise Fatio and illustrated by Roger Duvoisin .
Two Planets ( German : Auf zwei Planeten , lit . On Two Planets , 1897 ) is an influential science fiction novel postulating intelligent life on Mars by Kurd Lasswitz .
Zeluco is a 1789 novel by Scottish author John Moore that centers on the vicious deeds of the eponymous anti - hero , the evil Italian nobleman Zeluco .
Saucer Country is a discontinued UFO mythology comic book series written by Paul Cornell and drawn by Ryan Kelly , published by Vertigo in 2012 and 2013 .
Wir Juden ( We Jews ) is a 1934 book by German rabbi Joachim Prinz that concerns Hitler 's rise to power as a demonstration of the defeat of liberalism and assimilation as a solution for the Jewish Question , and advocated a Zionist alternative to save German Jews .
Fragrant Harbour ( 2002 ) is a novel by author John Lanchester .
Cligès is a poem by the medieval French poet Chrétien de Troyes , dating from around 1176 .
Three Hundred Years Hence is a utopian science fiction novel by author Mary Griffith .
The Merlin Conspiracy is a children 's fantasy novel by Diana Wynne Jones , published by HarperCollins in April 2003 , simultaneously in Britain and America .
The Amelia Peabody series is a series of nineteen historical mystery novels and one non - fiction companion volume written by Egyptologist Barbara Mertz ( 1927 - 2013 ) under the pen name Elizabeth Peters .
Prisoner 489 is a horror novella written by American author Joe R. Lansdale .
The Cloister and the Hearth ( 1861 ) is an historical novel by the English author Charles Reade .
Brooklyn August is a poem by Stephen King that first appeared in 1971 in Io magazine and was later collected in King 's Nightmares & Dreamscapes in 1993 .
Bookless in Baghdad is a 2005 book by author Shashi Tharoor that consists of a collection of previously published articles , book reviews and columns on writers , books and literary musings .
`` Le Bateau ivre '' ( `` The Drunken Boat '' ) is a 100-line verse - poem written in 1871 by Arthur Rimbaud .
The Earth After Us is a 2008 non - fiction book by Jan Zalasiewicz about the geological legacy that humans might one day leave behind them .
The Africa House is a 1999 biography by British journalist and writer Christina Lamb .
En rade ( English : Becalmed , A Haven or Stranded ) is a novel by the French writer Joris - Karl Huysmans .
The Hood 's Army Trilogy is a trilogy of young adult science fiction novels by Christopher Evans , written under the pseudonym of Nathan Elliott and published in 1986 .
That Hideous Strength ( subtitled A Modern Fairy - Tale for Grown - Ups ) is a 1945 novel by C. S. Lewis , the final book in Lewis 's theological science fiction Space Trilogy .
The Piratica Series is a series of young adult fantasy novels by Tanith Lee .
Future Evolution is a book written by paleontologist Peter Ward and illustrated by Alexis Rockman .
The One Percent Doctrine ( ISBN 0 - 7432 - 7109 - 2 ) is a nonfiction book by Pulitzer Prize -- winning journalist Ron Suskind about America 's hunt for terrorists since September 11th , 2001 .
I 'm Off ( French : Je m'en vais ) is a 1999 novel by the French writer Jean Echenoz .
The Dolphins of Laurentum is a historical novel by Caroline Lawrence published on February 6 , 2003 by Orion Books .
A Pair of Blue Eyes is a novel by Thomas Hardy , published in 1873 , first serialised between September 1872 and July 1873 .
The Borrible Trilogy is a series of young adult books written by English writer Michael de Larrabeiti .
Asterix and the Secret Weapon is the twenty - ninth volume of the Asterix comic book series and the fifth by Albert Uderzo alone .
Ubik ( /ˈjuːbɨk/ EW - bik ) is a 1969 science fiction novel by American writer Philip K. Dick .
The Tribes and the States is a book written by American child prodigy William James Sidis that outlines the history of the Native Americans , focusing mostly on the Northeastern tribes and continuing up to the mid-19th century .
The Green Years is a 1944 novel by A. J. Cronin which traces the formative years of an Irish orphan , Robert Shannon , who is sent to live with his draconian maternal grandparents in Scotland .
The Languages of Tolkien 's Middle - earth is a book on the languages of Middle - earth by Ruth S. Noel .
The Chinese Gold Murders is a gong'an historical mystery novel written by Robert van Gulik and set in Imperial China ( roughly speaking the Tang Dynasty ) .
The Night at the Museum , published in 1993 , is a children 's picture book written and illustrated by Milan Trenc .
The Diary of Samuel Marchbanks , published by Clarke , Irwin in 1947 , is the first of the Samuel Marchbanks books by Canadian novelist and journalist Robertson Davies .
Summer of the Aliens is a semi - autobiographical , 1990s play written by Louis Nowra .
Beautiful Bastard is an erotic romance novel by Christina Hobbs and Lauren Billings under the singular pen name of Christina Lauren .
The Condition of the Working Class in England is a 1845 book by the German philosopher Friedrich Engels , a study of the industrial working class in Victorian England .
Marriage in Heaven ( Romanian : Nuntă în cer ) is a 1938 novel by the Romanian writer Mircea Eliade .
`` The Fir - Tree '' ( Danish : Grantræet ) is a literary fairy tale by Danish poet and author Hans Christian Andersen ( 1805 - -1875 ) .
The Transcendence of the Ego ( French : La Transcendance de l'ego : Esquisse d'une description phénomenologique ) is a philosophical and psychological essay written by Jean - Paul Sartre in 1934 and published in 1936 .
`` A Guide to Berlin '' is a short story by Vladimir Nabokov , first published in 1925 .
A Dubious Legacy ( 1992 ) is a novel written by the British author Mary Wesley .
Journey Through the Impossible ( French : Voyage à travers l'impossible ) is an 1882 fantasy play written by Jules Verne , with the collaboration of Adolphe d'Ennery .
Jumping the Queue ( 1983 ) is British novelist Mary Wesley´s first adult novel , published when the author was seventy years old .
Bully for Brontosaurus ( 1991 ) is the fifth volume of collected essays by the Harvard paleontologist Stephen Jay Gould .
Involuntary Witness ( Italian : Testimone Inconsapevole ) is a legal thriller by Italian writer Gianrico Carofiglio , published originally in 2002 and translated into English by Patrick Creagh in 2005 .
Hans - Hermann Hoppe , who wrote the introduction to later editions of the book , described The Ethics of Liberty as Murray Rothbard 's second magnum opus , the other being Man , Economy , and State ( 1962 ) .
Travels with My Aunt ( 1969 ) is a novel written by English author Graham Greene .
Allies and Aliens is a single - volume work encompassing the novels The Torch of Honor and Rogue Powers by Roger MacBride Allen .
Indigenous Peoples in International Law ( ISBN 0 - 19517 - 350 - 3 ) is a book written by James Anaya .
No Time Like the Present is a 2012 novel by South African writer Nadine Gordimer .
The Fairy Gunmother ( 1987 , orig . French : La fée carabine ) is a comic novel by the French novelist Daniel Pennac , the second in his Malaussène saga .
More Pricks Than Kicks is a collection of short prose by Samuel Beckett , first published in 1934 .
The Book of My Lives is the first book of nonfiction by the Bosnian - American novelist Aleksandar Hemon .
Were You Always an Italian ? is a memoir written by American author Maria Laurino and published by W.W. Norton in 2000 .
The Edge of Sadness is a novel by the American author Edwin O'Connor .
Jixiao Xinshu ( simplified Chinese : 纪效新书 ; traditional Chinese : 紀效新書 ; pinyin : Jìxiào xīnshū ) or New Treatise on Military Efficiency was a military manual written by the Chinese general Qi Jiguang ( 戚继光 ) of the Ming dynasty .
The Alto Wore Tweed is the first novel in the St. Germaine mystery series by Mark Schweizer .
The Posthumous Memoirs of Bras Cubas ( Portuguese : Memorias Posthumas de Braz Cubas , modern spelling Memórias Póstumas de Brás Cubas ) , often subtitled as the Epitaph of a Small Winner , is a novel by the Brazilian writer Joaquim Maria Machado de Assis .
The Sorrows of Young Werther ( German : Die Leiden des jungen Werthers ) is an epistolary , loosely autobiographical novel by Johann Wolfgang von Goethe , first published in 1774 .

The New Confessions ( 1987 ) is a novel of the Scottish writer William Boyd .
Home from the Sea ( 2012 ) is a fantasy novel written by Mercedes Lackey and part of her Elemental Masters series .
The Ten Teacups ( U.S. title : The Peacock Feather Murders ) , is a locked room mystery by American mystery writer John Dickson Carr , writing as Carter Dickson .

The Small Rain is a semi - autobiographical novel by Madeleine L'Engle , about the many difficulties in the life of talented pianist Katherine Forrester between the ages of 10 and 19 .

Je voudrais pas crever ( I would n't want to croak ) is a collection of poetry by French author Boris Vian , published posthumously in 1962 .

Whittington Landon , the son of John Landon from Tedstone , Herefordshire , matriculated at the University of Oxford as a member of Worcester College on 13 October 1775 , aged 17 .
Adrian Bawtree was educated at Christ 's Hospital before he attended the Royal Academy of Music and was organ scholar at St Bride 's Church , Fleet Street .
Sharon Lechter graduated from Florida State University with an Accounting degree and Magna Cum Laude honors .
Jamie Thomas King was born in London , England and educated at Dulwich College , Fine Arts College and the London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art . He is the son of American screen writer Laura Lamson and English television director Christopher King .
Henry Moseley had been a very promising schoolboy at Summer Fields School ( where one of the four ' leagues ' is named after him ) , and he was awarded a King 's scholarship to attend Eton College .
Born in Verviers ( Belgium ) in 1929 , Jacques Drèze did undergraduate economics at the nearby Université de Liège , and then a Ph.D. at Columbia University , with a thesis on `` Individual Decision Making under Partially Controllable Uncertainty '' supervised by William Vickrey .
Born in Athens , Greece to a prominent war family from Arcadia , Miltos Manetas moved to Milan at the age of 20 , where he attended the Brera Academy .
Gwendolyn Cartledge ( born 1943 ) is professor in the School of Physical Activity and Educational Services at the Ohio State University ( Cartledge , 2009 ) , specializing in methods for teaching social skills to children with and without disabilities ) .
Despite studying drama at the University of Manchester Alison Newman did not work as an actress for almost ten years after graduating .
Ursula Goodenough , daughter of Erwin Ramsdell Goodenough and Evelyn Goodenough Pitcher , earned a B.A. in zoology from Barnard College , an M.A. in zoology at Columbia University and her Ph.D. in Biology at Harvard University .
Adrian Nigel Goring - Morris is a British - born Archaeologist and a Professor at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in Israel .
Sarah Morgan - Silvester ( born 1959 ) was the Chancellor of the University of British Columbia from November 19 , 2008 , through the end of her second three - year term on June 30 , 2014 .
Max Boot was educated at the University of California , Berkeley ( BA , History , 1991 ) and Yale University ( MA , Diplomatic History , 1992 ) .
Henry Ossian Flipper ( 21 March 1856 -- 3 May 1940 ) was an American soldier , former slave , and the first African American to graduate from the United States Military Academy at West Point in 1877 , earning a commission as a 2nd lieutenant in the US Army .
Marilene Oliver gained a BA in Fine Art Printmaking and Photomedia at Central Saint Martins College of Art and Design and an MA in Fine Art Printmaking at the Royal College of Art , both in London .
Van H. Vu ( Vietnamese : Vũ Hà Văn ) is a Vietnamese mathematician , Percey F. Smith Professor of Mathematics at Yale University .
Maud Menten was born in Port Lambton , Ontario and studied medicine at the University of Toronto ( B.A. 1904 , M.B. 1907 , M.D. 1911 ) .
For the most part , Franklin Peale 's education was informal , though he took some classes at the University of Pennsylvania .
Christopher McDonnell studied architecture before moving on to a fashion degree at the Royal College of Art under Janey Ironside .
Born in 1849 , Bernard Loder studied law in Amsterdam at the Athenaeum Illustre of Amsterdam , the predecessor to the University of Amsterdam , and afterward studied at University of Leiden .
Known variously in his cricket career as `` Kumar Narayan '' or `` Hitendra Narayan '' , he was educated at Eton College and Cambridge University and was a forceful right - handed batsman .
Born into a noble family on 12 August 1861 , Wilmot Vyvyan was educated at Charterhouse and Trinity College , Cambridge .
A graduate of Edinburgh College of Art , Duncan Rennie worked extensively in Scottish Film and Television behind the camera before developing his career as an actor .
Charles Champion ( born 1955 near Paris ) , who holds a MSc from Stanford University , has been Airbus 380 's Executive Vice President Engineering since 1 April 2010 and a member of the Airbus Executive Committee .
Dirk ter Haar ( Dr. , B.Sc . , M.Sc . , MA , D.Sc . , FRSE ) studied physics at Leiden University , was research fellow of Niels Bohr in Copenhagen , and received his Ph.D. in Leiden from Hendrik Kramers for a dissertation on the origin of the solar system .
Gordon Welchman was educated at Marlborough College and then studied mathematics as a scholar at Trinity College , Cambridge from 1925 to 1928 .
The family lived in Hyde Park , and John Paul Stevens attended the University of Chicago Laboratory School .
Tatiana Grindenko ( Russian : Татьяна Тихоновна Гринденко ; born 1946 ) is a Russian violinist and Meritorious Artist who graduated from the Moscow Conservatory and then became an assistant to Yuri Yankelevich .
Noah Rosenberg is a geneticist working in evolutionary biology , human genetics , and population genetics , now Associate Professor at Stanford University .
William Delaune D.D. ( 14 April 1659 -- 23 May 1728 ) was an English clergyman and academic , President of St John 's College , Oxford , and chaplain to Queen Anne .
Andreas Hackethal earned his degrees in Business Administration from Goethe University in Frankfurt and the University of Iowa .
Stuart McInally is a former headboy of George Watson 's College , and started his professional career in the 2010/2011 season .
He was the illegitimate son of Sir John Ingilby , 4th Baronet and educated at Emmanuel College , Cambridge .
Kurt Akeley received a B.E.E. from the University of Delaware in 1980 , and an M.S.E.E. from Stanford University in 1982 .
Sandra Quackenbush received her bachelor 's degree in animal science nutrition from Ohio State University in 1979 , obtained her Masters in retroviral pathogenesis from Colorado State University in 1987 and her Ph.D. also in retroviral pathogenesis in 1994 from Colorado State University .
Sangeeta N. Bhatia , M.D. , Ph.D. ( b. 1968 ) is an Indian American biological engineer and professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology ( MIT ) in Cambridge , Massachusetts , United States .
Gernot Heiser ( born 1957 ) is a Scientia Professor and the John Lions Chair for operating systems at the University of New South Wales ( UNSW ) .
Henry Carter Adams ( December 31 , 1851 -- August 11 , 1921 ) was a U.S. economist and Professor of Political Economy and finance at the University of Michigan .
Bettina Goislard ( 11 November 1974 -- 16 November 2003 ) was a French employee of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees ( UNHCR ) , assigned to its mission in Afghanistan .
Eric Mazur ( born November 14 , 1954 ) is a physicist and educator at Harvard University , and an entrepreneur in technology start - ups for the educational and technology markets .
Richard Mellon Scaife ( July 3 , 1932 -- July 4 , 2014 ) was an American billionaire , a principal heir to the Mellon banking , oil , and aluminum fortune , and the owner and publisher of the Pittsburgh Tribune - Review .
Aviv Regev is a computational biologist at the Broad Institute of MIT and Harvard , an associate professor in the department of biology at Massachusetts Institute of Technology and an Early Career Scientist at Howard Hughes Medical Institute .
Michael Kißener ( born 3 December 1960 , in Bonn ) is a German historian and Professor at the University of Mainz .
Leslie Hill is professor of French at the University of Warwick .
William H. Tucker is an American professor of psychology at Rutgers University and the author of several books critical of race science .
Kurt Weiland is a native of Austria and an executive in the Church of Scientology International .
Georgiann Davis is an assistant professor of sociology at University of Nevada , Las Vegas and formerly held a similar position at Southern Illinois University Edwardsville .
William Revelle ( born c. 1944 ) is a psychology professor at Northwestern University working in personality psychology .
Wilfried Feldenkirchen was born in Cologne and studied history , English studies and economics at the University of Bonn .
Sharon Inkelas is a Professor and former Chair of the Linguistics Department at the University of California , Berkeley .
Judith Brett ( born 1949 , Melbourne ) is a professor of politics at La Trobe University , Melbourne , Australia .
Charles C. Steidel ( born October 14 , 1962 Ithaca , New York ) is an American astronomer , and Lee A. DuBridge Professor of Astronomy at California Institute of Technology .
Christina Gonzalez is a news reporter for FOX 11 ( KTTV ) in Los Angeles .
Victor Hugo Benioff ( September 14 , 1899 -- February 1 , 1968 ) was an American seismologist and a professor at the California Institute of Technology .
David Shambaugh ( Chinese : 沈大伟,born January 18 , 1953 ) is a professor of political science and international affairs at the George Washington University in Washington DC , as well as a non - resident senior fellow at the Brookings Institution .
Tenzin Priyadarshi ( The Venerable Tenzin Priyadarshi ) is the president and CEO of the Dalai Lama Center for Ethics and Transformative Values ) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology ( MIT ) .
Heather Lechtman is an American materials scientist and archaeologist , and Director , Center for Materials Research in Archaeology and Ethnology ( CMRAE ) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology .
Adam Drewnowski ( born c. 1947 ) is a professor of epidemiology at the University of Washington and the director of the Center for Public Health Nutrition at the University 's School of Public Health .
Carlos D. Bustamante is a population geneticist working at Stanford University .
Rob Carter ( born 1949 ) is an American professor of typography and graphic design at Virginia Commonwealth University .
Richard B. Sewall ( 11 February 1908 - 16 April 2003 ) was a professor of English at Yale University , and author of the influential works The Life of Emily Dickinson and The Vision of Tragedy .
Benoît Duteurtre is currently a journalist writing for several French newspapers as Marianne , le Figaro and Paris - Match and presents a radio show producer for France Musique , a French public radio .
Hannah Valantine , M.D. is the Chief Officer for Scientific Workforce Diversity at the United States National Institutes of Health .
John Macnaghten Whittaker FRS ( 7 March 1905 - -29 January 1984 ) was a British mathematician and Vice - Chancellor of the University of Sheffield from 1953 to 1965 .
Dewitt H. Parker ( 1885 - -1949 ) was a professor of philosophy at the University of Michigan .
Alfreð Gíslason ( born 7 September 1959 in Akureyri , Iceland ) is a former player and coach for the Iceland national handball team and the current coach of THW Kiel .
Hans Hunziker ( August 2 , 1878 -- December 17 , 1941 ) was a Swiss psychiatrist , professor of social medicine at University of Basel , head of the Cantonal Health Office of Basel - Stadt , and notable for his contributions on neuropsychiatry .
Pierre Amoyal ( born in Paris , 22 June 1949 ) , is a French violinist and is the artistic director of the Conservatory of Lausanne .
Miroljub Jevtić ( born 1955 in Vranje , Serbia ) is Serbian Politologist of religion and professor at the Faculty of Political Science , University of Belgrade .
George Wegner Paus ( 14 October 1882 -- 22 December 1923 ) was a Norwegian lawyer and Director at the Norwegian Employers ' Confederation .
John William Gregg ( January 8 , 1880 , New Hampshire - 1969 Berkeley ) , was a 20th - century professor of landscape architecture at the University of California , Berkeley .
Peter Lawrenson , BSc , MSc , DSc , FIEE , FIEEE , FRS , FREng is an Emeritus Professor of Electrical Engineering at the University of Leeds who contributed to the development of switched reluctance ( SR ) drive technology .
Bogdan Czaykowski ( b. 1932 , Rivno , Ukraine , then in Poland , ; d. 2007 , Canada ) was a Polish Canadian poet , essayist , literary translator and literary critic , professor emeritus and former Dean at the University of British Columbia .
Steve Alpern is a professor of Operational Research at the University of Warwick , where he recently moved after working for many years at the London School of Economics .
Sir Basil Markesinis QC , DCL , FBA ( born July 10 , 1944 ) is a scholar of law and Jamail Regents Professor at the University of Texas at Austin , and was Professor of Common and Civil Law , University College London .
Martin Campbell - Kelly is an Emeritus Professor at the University of Warwick who has specialised in the history of computing .
Mark Holtzapple is a chemical engineering professor at Texas A&M University .
Colin P. Smith ( born 1955/1956 ( age 58 - -59 ) ) FRS FREng FRAeS FIMechE CBE is Director of Engineering and Technology at Rolls - Royce plc .
Paul Glendinning is a Professor of Applied Mathematics , in the School of Mathematics at the University of Manchester who is known for his work on dynamical systems , specifically models of the time - evolution of complex mathematical or physical processes .
John Brignell , Ph.D. , is a retired Professor of Industrial Instrumentation at University of Southampton .
Neil Guppy ( born December 1 , 1949 ) is a professor and sociologist at the University of British Columbia in Vancouver , Canada .
Jacob Milgrom spent most of his career at the University of California , Berkeley , where he headed the Department of Near Eastern Studies .
Robert Bagley is a professor of Chinese art history and archaeology in the Department of Art and Archaeology at Princeton University .
Jeffrey R. Di Leo is Dean of the School of Arts and Sciences and Professor of English and Philosophy at the University of Houston-- Victoria .
Anne Forrester Holloway ( 1941 -- June 23 , 2006 ) was an American diplomat whom held offices with the United States Department of State and the United Nations .
Annette Zippelius is a German physicist at the University of Göttingen .

Nick Salvatore ( born Brooklyn , New York ) is an American historian , and Maurice and Hinda Neufeld Founders Professor of Industrial and Labor Relations and Professor of American Studies at Cornell University .

John F. Benton ( 1931 Philadelphia - February 25 , 1988 Pasadena ) was the Doris and Henry Dreyfuss Professor of History , at the California Institute of Technology .
Shmuel Toledano ( Hebrew : שמואל טולידאנו‎ , born 16 January 1921 ) is an Israeli former Mossad employee and politician who served as a member of the Knesset for the Democratic Movement for Change and Shinui between 1977 and 1981 .
Martha Greenblatt , a chemist , researcher , and faculty member at Rutgers University , New Brunswick , New Jersey , is the only female chair of a science department in the School of Arts and Science to date ( Jan 2008 ) .
Athanasios Angelopoulos ( Greek : Αθανάσιος Αγγελόπουλος ) ( born November 6 , 1939 in Katerini , Northern Greece ) is a Professor of Pastoral Theology at the Aristotle University of Thessaloniki ; founder and in - honour president of the Institute for National and Religious Studies ( Karipion Institute ) .
Marc Gopin is director of the Center for World Religions , Diplomacy and Conflict Resolution , and James H. Laue Professor at George Mason University .
Richard J. Samuels ( born November 2 , 1951 ) is an American academic , political scientist , author , Japanologist , Ford International Professor of Political Science and director of the Center for International Studies at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology .
Marc Kamionkowski ( born 1965 , Cleveland , Ohio ) is an American theoretical physicist and currently Professor of Physics and Astronomy at Johns Hopkins University .
Ian Katz ( born 1967 - -68 ) is a British journalist who is the editor of the Newsnight current affairs programme on BBC Two .
Yoav Freund ( Hebrew : יואב פרוינד‎ ) is an Israeli professor of computer science at the University of California , San Diego who mainly works on machine learning , probability theory and related fields and applications .
Susumu Tachi ( born January 1 , 1946 ) is a professor of Graduate School of Media Design at Keio University and Professor Emeritus of the University of Tokyo .
Peter Funke studied history and German studies at the University of Münster from 1969 to 1974 .
Deepak Nayyar ( born 1946 ) is Professor of Economics at Jawaharlal Nehru University , New Delhi .
Ivo Banac ( Croatian pronunciation : ( iːʋo baːnats ) ) ( born March 1 , 1947 ) is a Croatian historian , a long - time history professor at Yale University and was a politician of the former Liberal Party in Croatia .
David Andrew Smith ( born March 5 , 1952 ) is the Deputy Director of the United Nations Information Office in Washington DC . He was formerly an award - winning TV correspondent with ITN and Channel 4 News .
Kenneth W. Bilby ( October 7 , 1918 -- August 1 , 1997 ) was a winner of the Legion of Honor , an executive vice president of RCA , and the author of The General , a book on David Sarnoff 's role in the creation of RCA and television .
Crawford Hallock Greenewalt , Jr. ( June 3 , 1937 -- May 4 , 2012 ) was a classical archaeologist at the University of California , Berkeley who made contributions to the study of Lydia through his excavations at Sardis .
Lisa M. Buttenheim ( born 1954 ) , a national of the United States , is the Special Representative and Head of the United Nations Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus ( UNFICYP ) .
Dr. Abdallah Daar is a Professor of Public Health Sciences at the Dalla Lana Faculty of Public Health , University of Toronto , with a cross - appointment in the department of Surgery .
Pat Keysell ( 7 June 1926 -- 31 October 2009 ) was a presenter of the BBC television series Vision On which ran from 1964 to 1976 .
David McCord Wright ( 1909 - -1968 ) was an American economist and educator at the University of Georgia .
Cristian Dumitru Popescu is a Romanian - American mathematician at the University of California , San Diego .
Murray Clarke is a Professor of Philosophy at Concordia University in Montreal , Quebec , Canada .
Ian Shapiro ( born 1956 ) is Sterling Professor of Political Science and Henry R. Luce Director of the MacMillan Center at Yale University .
John Corvino ( born 1969 ) is an American author , lecturer , and professor of philosophy at Wayne State University .
Jüri Uluots ( 13 January 1890 -- 9 January 1945 ) was an Estonian prime minister , journalist , prominent attorney and distinguished Professor and Dean of the Faculty of Law at the University of Tartu .
Paul Fredericq ( 12 August 1850 -- 23 March 1920 ) was a Belgian historian at Ghent University active in the promotion of the use of the Dutch language in Belgium .
Catherine Gallagher ( born 16 February 1945 ) is a historicist literary critic and Victorianist , and is Professor of English at the University of California , Berkeley .
Leonard Parkin ( 2 June 1929 - 20 September 1993 ) was a British TV journalist and newscaster who worked for both the BBC and ITN .
Aksel C. Wiin - Nielsen ( 17 February 1924 -- 26 April 2010 ) was a Danish professor of meteorology at University of Copenhagen , University of Michigan , Director of the ECMWF , and Secretary - General of WMO .
John Orrell ( December 31 , 1934 -- September 16 , 2003 ) was an author , theatre historian , and English professor at the University of Alberta .
Gary C. Cornia is an American professor who was the eighth Dean of the Marriott School of Management at Brigham Young University .
Sam Cowen is a South African radio DJ and co - host of the morning show The Breakfast express weekdays on Johannesburg local radio station 94.7 Highveld Stereo .
Oliver Rathkolb ( born 3 November 1955 in Vienna ) is an Austrian historian and professor for contemporary history at the University of Vienna .
Eugenio Coșeriu ( Romanian : Eugen Coșeriu , pronounced ( e.uˈd͡ʒen koˈʃerju ) ; July 27 , 1921 -- September 7 , 2002 ) was a linguist that specialized in Romance languages at the University of Tübingen , author of over 50 books , honorary member of the Romanian Academy .
John McEldowney is professor of law at the University of Warwick and former World Bank visiting fellow in the Supreme Tribunal of Justice in Venezuela .
Dan Damon is a BBC journalist and radio broadcaster who presents World Update for the BBC World Service .
Lene Auestad is a philosopher from the University of Oslo .

Rowland Leonard Miall ( 6 November 1914 -- 24 February 2005 ) was a broadcaster and administrator at the BBC for 35 years , from 1939 to 1974 .
Penelope Deutscher is a professor of philosophy at Northwestern University whose work focuses on French philosophy from the 20th and 21st centuries and gender theory .
Luigi Gregori ( 1819 - -1896 ) was an Italian artist who worked at the Vatican and served as artist in residence and professor at the University of Notre Dame .
Mete Sozen is Kettelhut Distinguished Professor of Structural Engineering at Purdue University , Indiana , United States .
Franz Baader ( 15 June 1959 , Spalt ) is a German computer scientist at Dresden University of Technology .

Hedvig Ulrika De la Gardie was the daughter of count Carl Julius De la Gardie and countess Magdalena Christina Stenbock .
Henrik Skadelår ( c. 1090 - 4 June 1134 ) was a Danish prince , the son of Svend Tronkræver , an illegitimate son of king Sweyn II of Denmark .

Estorre Visconti , or Astorre according to other sources ( 1346 -- 7 January 1413 ) , was one of the many illegitimate sons of the famous Bernabò Visconti , Lord of Milan and already deposed by his nephew Gian Galeazzo Visconti in 1385 .
Giovanni Kessler is the son of Bruno Kessler ( 1924 - -1991 ) , a former President of the Autonomous Province of Trento and vice - minister to the Interior .
Francisco Parra Capó was born in Ponce in 1867 , the son of Francisco Parra Duperón and Eufemia Capó Ortiz de la Renta Bermudas .

Orderic Vitalis described Isabel of Conches , daughter of Simon I de Montfort , as brave as `` several Amazons and the legendary Camilla , who fought as ally of the Italian king Turnus in the Aeneid . ''
Jia Chong 's father Jia Kui was a military general of Cao Wei and considered an epitome of faithfulness to the state .
Ali - Royal was a `` leggy , workmanlike '' bay horse with a white star and white markings on both of his hind feet , bred at the Coolmore Stud in County Tipperary by Charles H. Wacker III . His sire , Royal Academy won the July Cup at Newmarket and the Breeders ' Cup Mile in 1990 .
Ramruma , a small , lightly - built chestnut filly with a white star , was bred at the Kentucky branch of her owner , Fahd bin Salman 's Newgate Stud , sired by Diesis out of the mare Princess of Man .
Sir Henry Fane KB , JP ( c. 1650 -- buried Basildon 12 January 1706 ) was the only son and heir of George Fane ( 1616 - -1663 ) of Hatton Garden , by his wife Dorothy daughter and heir of James Horsey of Honnington , Warwickshire .
Major Malcolm Munthe MC ( 30 January 1910 - -24 November 1995 ) was a British soldier , writer , and curator , and son of the famous Swedish doctor and writer Axel Munthe and his second wife Hilda Pennington - Mellor .
At Talaq was sired by Roberto out of the mare My Nord ( by Vent du Nord ) .

In Greek mythology , Oncius ( Ὅγκιος Onkios ) or Oncus ( Ὅγκος Onkos ) was a son of Apollo and a ruler over Oncium ( Onkeion ) , a region of Arcadia adjacent to Thelpusa , as well as eponym of a city Oncae .
Raymond Phélypeaux was son of Louis Phélypeaux , lord of La Cave and La Vrillière .

Chief 's Crown was a son of leading sire Danzig and Six Crowns , who was by Secretariat and out of the 1974 U.S. Filly Triple Crown winner Chris Evert .
William VIII of Jülich , Count of Ravensberg ( c. 1380 -- 22 November 1428 ) was the youngest son of William VII of Jülich , 1st Duke of Berg and Anna of the Palatinate .

William Seymour , 3rd Duke of Somerset ( 1654 -- 12 December 1671 ) was the son of Henry Seymour , Lord Beauchamp and Mary Capell .

Union Rags is a bay with a white blaze sired by Dixie Union who won the Haskell Invitational Handicap in 2000 before becoming a successful stallion .
Christian Cannabich was the third child of Martin Friedrich Cannabich ( 1690 - -1773 ) , a flautist , oboist and music teacher at the Mannheim court .

Avoise de Craon ( before 1178-c . 1230 ) daughter of Maurice II de Craon and wife of Guy V de Laval .
In Greek mythology , Dorus ( Ancient Greek : Δῶρος ) is a son of Hellen who was the eponymous founder of the Dorians .
Pieter Brueghel the Younger was born in Brussels , the oldest son of the famous sixteenth - century Netherlandish painter Pieter Brueghel the Elder ( known as `` Peasant Brueghel '' ) and Mayken Coecke van Aelst .

Darara was a small , lightly built bay mare with a faint white star and a white sock on her left hind leg bred in Ireland by his owner Aga Khan IV . Her sire Top Ville was an Irish - bred , French - trained horse which won the Prix du Jockey Club in 1979 .
Khun Lo , legendary founder of the city of Luang Prabang , was the eldest of the seven sons of the Khun Borom , and is credited as being the first of the prehistoric Lao monarchs .

Robert Ellsberg , son of Daniel Ellsberg is the editor - in - chief and publisher of Orbis Books , the publishing arm of Maryknoll .
Alfonso de Cartagena was the second son of Rabbi Paul of Burgos , who converted from Judaism to Christianity in 1390 or 1391 .
Catherine Carey was born in about 1524 , the daughter of Sir William Carey of Aldenham in Hertfordshire , Gentleman of the Privy Chamber and Esquire of the Body to Henry VIII , and his wife Mary Boleyn , who had once been a mistress of the king .
Rupert , Count of Nassau - Sonnenberg ( c. 1340 -- 4 September 1390 ) , nicknamed the Bellicose , was a son of Gerlach I , Count of Nassau and his second wife , Irmgard of Hohenlohe .
Petar Zrinski was born in Vrbovec , a small town near Zagreb , the son of Juraj V Zrinski and Magdalena Szechy .
Bianca de ' Medici , usually known as Bia de ' Medici , ( c. 1536 -- 1 March 1542 ) was the illegitimate daughter of Cosimo I de ' Medici , Grand Duke of Tuscany , born before his first marriage .
Osmán Morote Barrionuevo known with the alias of Comrade Nicolas was one of Efraín Morote Best 's sons .

The Royal Irish Rangers ( 27th ( Inniskilling ) , 83rd and 87th ) was a regular infantry regiment of the British Army with a relatively short existence , formed in 1968 and later merged with several other Irish regiments in 1992 to form the Royal Irish Regiment .
Richard Henry Stevens ( 9 April 1893 -- 12 February 1967 ) was a major in the British Army and from 1939 Head of the Passport Control Office ( PCO ) of the British Secret Intelligence Service in the Netherlands .
Air Vice Marshal Raymond Collishaw CB , DSO & Bar , OBE , DSC , DFC ( 22 November 1893 -- 28 September 1976 ) was a distinguished Canadian fighter pilot , squadron leader , and commanding officer who served in the Royal Naval Air Service ( RNAS ) and later the Royal Air Force .
Frederick Behne ( October 3 , 1873 -- February 11 , 1918 ) was a fireman first class serving in the United States Navy who received the Medal of Honor for bravery .
Sir Frescheville Holles ( 8 June 1642 -- 28 May 1672 ) was an English Royal Navy officer and politician who sat in the House of Commons from 1666 to 1672 .
Sandra E. Adams is a Rear admiral in the United States Navy .
Major - General Christopher Haslett Elliott , CVO , CBE ( born 26 May 1947 ) is a former senior British Army officer who served as Defence Services Secretary from 2001 to 2004 .

Klingermans Run ( also known as Klingerman Run ) is a tributary of Catawissa Creek in Columbia County , Pennsylvania , in the United States .
The Speyerbach is a left tributary of the Rhine in the Palatinate part of Rhineland - Palatinate .
The Oust ( Breton : Oud ) is a river in Brittany , France , right tributary of the Vilaine .
The Rideau River is an Eastern Ontario river which flows north from Upper Rideau Lake and empties into the Ottawa River at Rideau Falls in Ottawa , Ontario .
The Cheremosh River ( Ukrainian : Черемош , Romanian : Ceremuş , Polish : Czeremosz ) is a river in western Ukraine , right - bank tributary of the Prut River .
The Nuthe is a river in Brandenburg , Germany , left tributary of the Havel .
Carnahan Run is a tributary of the Kiskiminetas River in Armstrong County in the U.S. state of Pennsylvania .
Cape Cod Bay is a large bay of the Atlantic Ocean adjacent to the U.S. state of Massachusetts .
The Kwilu River is a major river that originates in Angola and flows north through Bandundu Province in the Democratic Republic of the Congo ( DRC ) to the city of Bandundu , where it joins the Kwango River just before this stream enters the Kasai River .
The Küsten Canal , also known as the Coastal Canal ( German : Küstenkanal ) , is a canal , about 70 kilometres ( 43 mi ) long , that links the Dortmund - Ems Canal with the Hunte and thus the Weser rivers .
The Choptank River is a major tributary of the Chesapeake Bay and the largest river on the Delmarva Peninsula .
The Ardila is a river of Spain and Portugal and a tributary of the Guadiana .
The Retreat River rises on the western slopes of the Great Dividing Range , near Shooters Hill , and flows generally to the south - west , before reaching its confluence with the Abercrombie River , near Hadley .
The headwaters of the Delatite River rise on the western slopes of the Victorian Alps and descend to flow into the Goulburn River within Lake Eildon .
The Gambia River ( formerly known as the River Gambra ) is a major river in West Africa , running 1,130 kilometres ( 700 mi ) from the Fouta Djallon plateau in north Guinea westward through Senegal and the Gambia to the Atlantic Ocean at the city of Banjul .
Blizzards Run ( also known as Blizzard Run or Blizzard 's Run ) is a tributary of Sechler Run in Montour County , Pennsylvania , in the United States .
The Maira is an Italian river , a right tributary of the Po , which runs through the province of Cuneo in eastern Piedmont .
The Örtze is a river in the North German state of Lower Saxony , which rises north of Munster in the Große Heide ( in the Raubkammer federal forest ) and , after 62 kilometres ( 39 mi ) , joins the Aller southeast of Winsen .
Uggerby Å rises in Sterup ( south of Hjørring ) and empties into Skagerrak .

Tarcutta Creek is mostly a perennial stream beginning approximately 13 kilometres ( 8.1 mi ) near Batlow and confluence with the Murrumbidgee River approximately 6 kilometres ( 3.7 mi ) southeast of Oura in the Riverina area in New South Wales , Australia .
West Morava ( Serbian : Западна Морава / Zapadna Morava , pronounced ( zâːpadnaː mɔ̝̌rav̞a ) ) , is a river in central Serbia , a 308 km - long longer headstream of the Great Morava , which it forms with the South Morava .
The river Canche ( Dutch : De Kwinte ) is one of the rivers that flow from the plateau of the southern Boulonnais and Picardy , into the English Channel .
Excalibosaurus ( meaning `` Excalibur 's lizard '' ) is a monotypic genus of marine prehistoric fish - like reptiles ( ichthyosaurs ) that lived during the Sinemurian stage ( approximately 196.5 ± 2 Ma to 189.6 ± 1.5 Ma ( million years ago ) ) of the Early Jurassic period in what is now England .
Arfvedsonite was discovered in 1823 and named for the Swedish chemist Johan August Arfwedson ( 1792 - -1841 ) .
The Boltzmann Medal ( or Boltzmann Award ) is the most important prize awarded to physicists that obtain new results concerning statistical mechanics ; it is named after the celebrated physicist Ludwig Boltzmann .
Duodenitis is inflammation of the duodenum .

In algebraic geometry , Chow 's moving lemma , named after Wei - Liang Chow , states : given algebraic cycles Y , Z on a nonsingular quasi - projective variety X , there is another algebraic cycle Z ' on X such that Z ' is rationally equivalent to Z and Y and Z ' intersect properly .

Szamanka ( Polish pronunciation : ( ʂaˈmaŋka ) , The Shaman ) is a Polish - French - Swiss film , released in 1996 , directed by Andrzej Żuławski and adapted from a screenplay by Manuela Gretkowska .
The Fatherless ( German : Die Vaterlosen ) is a 2011 Austrian drama film written and directed by Marie Kreutzer .
Embrace of the Serpent ( Spanish : El abrazo de la serpiente ) is a 2015 Colombian adventure drama film directed by Ciro Guerra .
La Ballade des Dalton is a 1978 French animated film written and directed by René Goscinny , Morris , Henri Gruel and Pierre Watrin starring the comic book character Lucky Luke .
Cries and Whispers ( Swedish : Viskningar och rop , lit . `` Whispers and Cries '' ) is a 1972 Swedish film written and directed by Ingmar Bergman and starring Harriet Andersson , Kari Sylwan , Ingrid Thulin and Liv Ullmann .
Le lourd passé de Lagaffe , written and drawn by Franquin and Jidéhem , is an album of the original Gaston Lagaffe series , numbered R5 .
`` Winter Madness '' is the eleventh episode of the fourth season of the American television comedy series 30 Rock , and the 69th overall episode of the series .
`` Two Days and Two Nights '' is the twenty - fifth episode ( production # 125 ) of the television series Star Trek : Enterprise .
`` The Making of Private Pike '' is the second episode of the ninth series of the British comedy series Dad 's Army that was originally transmitted on 9 October 1977 .
`` The Naked Now '' is the third episode of the first season of the American science fiction television series Star Trek : The Next Generation , originally aired on October 5 , 1987 in broadcast syndication in the United States .
Ahmet Pezük ( born 6 August 1987 ) is a Turkish male former volleyball player .
Marina Canetti ( born January 24 , 1983 in Rio de Janeiro ) is a female water polo player from Brazil , who won the bronze medal with the Brazil women 's national water polo team at the 2003 Pan American Games .
Andrus Veerpalu ( born 8 February 1971 in Pärnu ) is a former and so far the most successful Estonian male cross country skier .
Sarah Dance was the female winner of the National Collegiate Athletic Association 's highest academic honor , the 2005 Walter Byers Award , in recognition of being the nation 's top female scholar - athlete .
Wu Wenxiong ( Chinese : 吳 文雄 born February 11 , 1981 ) is a male weightlifter from PR China .
Leslie Newman is a screenwriter who co - wrote the first three Superman films with husband David Newman , who died in 2003 .
Yvonne Loriod ( 20 January 1924 -- 17 May 2010 ) was a French pianist , teacher , and composer , and the second wife of composer Olivier Messiaen .
In 1893 , John Henry Comstock and Simon Henry Gage founded the Comstock Publishing Company in order to make textbooks on microscopy , histology , and entomology available at a reasonable price to students and to publish the works of Anna Botsford Comstock on nature study .
Helen Levitov Sobell ( March 13 , 1918 - April 15 , 2002 ) was an American teacher , scientist and activist , and the former wife of convicted spy Morton Sobell .
In 1998 , twelve years after Samora Machel 's death , Graça Machel married Nelson Mandela , President of South Africa , thus becoming the only woman to have been First Lady of two countries .
Yvonne Artaud ( Lyon , 1924 - Pondicherry , 5 August 2009 ) was a French educator , ethnologist , psychologist and artist , and was the aide of the thinker and philosopher Medhananda .
Barbara of Portugal ( Maria Madalena Bárbara Xavier Leonor Teresa Antónia Josefa ; 4 December 1711 -- 27 August 1758 ) was an Infanta of Portugal and later Queen of Spain as wife of Ferdinand VI of Spain .

Paul Dini and his wife , magician Misty Lee , have created an on - line interview feature called Monkey Talk that runs at Kevin Smith 's website , Quick Stop Entertainment.com .
Josette Rey - Debove , born November 16 , 1929 in Calais ( Pas - de - Calais ) , France and died February 22 , 2005 in Senegal , was a lexicographer and semiologist , wife and colleague of Alain Rey .
Agnes of Faucigny ( died 11 August 1268 ) was suo jure Dame of Faucigny , and countess consort of Savoy by virtue of her marriage in 1236 to Peter II , Count of Savoy .
Philippine Welser ( 1527 -- 24 April 1580 ) was the morganatic wife of Ferdinand II , Archduke of Austria .
Gloria Foster was married to the actor Clarence Williams III in 1967 .

Najwa bin Laden ( born c. 1959 ) , née Ghanem , is a Syrian woman who was the first wife and first cousin of Osama bin Laden .
Jacob Pietersz Olycan ( 1596 -- 1638 ) , was a brewer , magistrate , and later mayor of Haarlem , best known today for his portrait by Frans Hals , pendant to the portrait of Aletta Hannemans , whom he married in Zwolle in 1624 .
Chipeta or White Singing Bird ( 1843 or 1844 - -August 1924 ) , was a Native American woman , and the second wife of Chief Ouray of the Uncompahgre Ute tribe .

Trichomycterus diatropoporos is a species of pencil catfish endemic to Brazil , where it occurs in the da Prata and Turvo river basins , tributaries of the das Antas river , in the Laguna dos Patos system in the state of Rio Grande do Sul .
Centris elegans is a bee species in the genus Centris found on Saint Vincent and Grenadines .
